<span id="freeTextContainer1343612258995317304">Touched on this multiple ways over the years including part of The Crusades with Liz Hardwick circa 1975-76 and Conn Igulden&apos;s historical fiction. Current reads are a little slow. Found this on my father in laws shelf. Always a good recommendation. The reviews here are extremely well written and accurate. If you&apos;re undecided about reading this, I recommend you read them. I would also offer that the maps are quite helpful, but don&apos;t really give a sense of the immense distance involved or how slow</span>
  <span id="freeText1343612258995317304" style="display:none">Touched on this multiple ways over the years including part of The Crusades with Liz Hardwick circa 1975-76 and Conn Igulden's historical fiction. Current reads are a little slow. Found this on my father in laws shelf. Always a good recommendation. The reviews here are extremely well written and accurate. If you're undecided about reading this, I recommend you read them. I would also offer that the maps are quite helpful, but don't really give a sense of the immense distance involved or how slowly everyone else moved compared to the Mongols on campaign. Or to just how challenging some of the terrain was to travel. Also, strongly recommend the bibliography for further reading. Towards the end, as the tale gets into the third/fourth generation from Chingis, it does get hard to follow the thread. Spent some time flipping back and forth to the family tree. </span>
