<div id="review_155596606" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/155596606" />
    <a title="Mosaic" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3607479-mosaic"><img alt="Mosaic" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/155596606?book_show_action=true">Mar 20, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mosaic" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mosaic" href="/user/show/3607479-mosaic">Mosaic</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer155596606" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer947117446202095273">As Chambers introduces in his preface, his aim is to tell a good story about the Mongols&apos; western campaigns. Insofar as that, he succeeds because of his very engaging style. The reader really gets a sense of the military behemoth that was the Mongol army under Chingis Khan, and the magnitude of threat it posed to the sedentary civilizations of Asia and Europe. At the same time, Chambers also makes sure he highlights the factional politics that had so divided Europe that neither could they stand </span>
  <span id="freeText947117446202095273" style="display:none">As Chambers introduces in his preface, his aim is to tell a good story about the Mongols' western campaigns. Insofar as that, he succeeds because of his very engaging style. The reader really gets a sense of the military behemoth that was the Mongol army under Chingis Khan, and the magnitude of threat it posed to the sedentary civilizations of Asia and Europe. At the same time, Chambers also makes sure he highlights the factional politics that had so divided Europe that neither could they stand a chance against the Mongol invasion nor did they have the fortitude to ally with them against the Muslims. The only reason Western Europe was saved from being swept in the destructive onslaught was because of pure chance. According to Chambers, anyway. There are some factual errors and interpretations that are considered outdated by scholars, but Chambers doesn't make any scholarly pretensions. His book is a great attempt at "popular history," weaving the numerous facts into a colorful narrative. </span>
  <a data-text-id="947117446202095273" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

